<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-11-14T16:36:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-11-14T16:36:00-05:00" n="1209" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1209">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/5494.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Consul at
                                    Acapulco</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi>.</head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Extract.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Consulate</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Acapulco</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-11-14T15:00:00-06:36">
                                    <hi rend="italic">November 14, 1912—3 p.m.</hi>
                                </date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>Rebel leader Padilla controls all coast region to north of Acapulco. All
                            Government troops have retreated to Acapulco.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Harry K. Pangburn.</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>